ily": "system-ui, -apple-system, \"system-ui\", \"Segoe UI\", Helvetica, Arial, sans-serif", "color": "rgb(26, 18, 16)", "backgroundColor": "rgb(253, 248, 242)", "display": "block", "position": "static", "borderTopColor": "rgb(26, 18, 16)", "borderRightColor": "rgb(26, 18, 16)", "borderBottomColor": "rgb(26, 18, 16)", "borderLeftColor": "rgb(26, 18, 16)", "borderTopWidth": "0px", "borderRightWidth": "0px", "borderBottomWidth": "0px", "borderLeftWidth": "0px", "borderTopLeftRadius": "0px", "borderTopRightRadius": "0px", "borderBottomLeftRadius": "0px", "borderBottomRightRadius": "0px", "paddingTop": "0px", "paddingRight": "0px", "paddingBottom": "0px", "paddingLeft": "0px", "marginTop": "0px", "marginRight": "0px", "marginBottom": "0px", "marginLeft": "0px", "textAlign": "start", "boxShadow": "none", "backgroundImage": "none"}, "htmlRect": {"x": 0, "y": 0, "width": 1440, "height": 2199.91, "bottom": 2199.91, "right": 1440, "area": 3167865}, "visibleText": "Copper Kettle Suppers Featured Recipe Ingredients Method Tips & Swaps About the Cook The Featured Supper Slow-Braised Lamb Shanks with White Bean Ragout Four hours, one heavy pot, and a quiet kitchen. Lamb shanks fall from the bone into a bed of cannellini beans loosened with anchovy and rosemary, finished with a long, mellow pour of dry vermouth that turns everything golden at the edges. A heavy copper pot at a slow tremor. Braised four hours; rested ten minutes; eaten without ceremony. Serves 4 Prep 25 min Cook 3 hr 20 min Start with the Pantry Origin From a Ligurian Kitchen This recipe began at my grandmother Adelina's stove in a narrow flat above a butcher's shop in Genoa, where the smell of bay leaves and seared lamb seeped into the wallpaper. She braised shanks the way other women said the rosary \u2014 patiently, in the same order, with absolute faith that nothing would be wasted. The white beans came from a paper sack on top of the cupboard, soaked overnight in a chipped enamel bowl. The anchovy was almost a secret; she would never have called it a flavour, only a salt. The dry vermouth was poured by eye, twice, the second time muttered as a blessing. What you have here is faithful to her method, translated for a domestic oven and a single quiet afternoon. If anything is sacred in this dish, it is the hour after the lid first goes on \u2014 when the kitchen turns warm and forgiving, and there is very little left to do but trust the pot. Read the Whole Recipe Four short pages, in the order you'll want them. Ingredients Method Tips & Swaps About the Cook \u00a9 Copper Kettle Suppers \u00b7 A single-recipe showcase \u00b7 teodora@copperkettlesuppers.test"}